Firſt, from hence he concludeth, That the Parliament are not to make Lawes to undo the People, nor perpetuate Heavy bu •
dens: There is no man that is in his Wits will ſay otherwiſe;
and no doubt but the Parliament will do otherwiſe; this Authour cannot charge them as yet with that. 'Tis true, that the charge of the late War hath been heavy; that the Care of the management of the War prevented them of ſettling the Government of the Nation; that they ſhould diſſolve before, is unreaſonable to expect: beſides, their own Vote hath decided that Controverſie, viz. That this Seſsion ſhall determine, May, 1660.
